WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.250 --> 00:00:03.449
Hello everyone in this week's After Effects scripting tutorial

00:00:03.449 --> 00:00:10.560
I'm going to be showing you how to better learn After Effects scripting by yourself, and some steps that I would take and recommend to do so.

00:00:10.560 --> 00:00:15.120
So as most of you know After Effects scripting can be very complicated at times.

00:00:15.879 --> 00:00:19.079
So sometimes it can seem really hard to get through learning it.

00:00:19.359 --> 00:00:24.389
I just wanted to go over a few tips and give you guys some tips and tricks of how I learned.

00:00:25.090 --> 00:00:32.250
So the first thing is to always reference the scripting guide and the UI guide. I'll have all the resources in the description

00:00:32.559 --> 00:00:33.780
including these links.

00:00:33.780 --> 00:00:38.520
But you basically want to make sure that you're always learning about what's inside of the scripting guide.

00:00:38.620 --> 00:00:45.090
Make sure you check old and new versions to see what features have been implemented recently, or what features are now obsolete.

00:00:45.399 --> 00:00:47.399
The scripting guide is very useful because

00:00:47.410 --> 00:00:54.779
everything is organized in an object mode,  so that we can actually see the hierarchy of how everything works inside of After Effects, from the

00:00:54.910 --> 00:00:59.129
Application level all the way down to the property or parameter level.

00:00:59.129 --> 00:01:03.719
And there's also these script UI which is designed for InDesign actually.

00:01:03.909 --> 00:01:07.469
But it does apply for any other types of scripts that you could be making.

00:01:08.080 --> 00:01:15.479
This document is basically just going to allow us to learn everything we need to know about making UIs. It even has included

00:01:16.060 --> 00:01:22.560
example code as well as images for what all the code does. So again this one will also be in the description.

00:01:23.500 --> 00:01:30.150
The next thing I would recommend is constant code review. If you're not reading a language when you're learning it,

00:01:30.150 --> 00:01:35.549
you're not going to be able to speak it or write it. So it's important to always be taking a look at at least

00:01:35.680 --> 00:01:37.180
some code.

00:01:37.180 --> 00:01:43.619
Whether it be syntactical and not even JavaScript, or just straight JavaScript Extended for After Effects.

00:01:44.710 --> 00:01:49.680
Inside of every version of After Effects inside of your support files.

00:01:50.500 --> 00:01:54.299
After Effects includes plenty of unencoded scripts that you can load up,

00:01:54.840 --> 00:01:59.600
check out the code inside, and learn all about scripting.

00:01:59.620 --> 00:02:06.420
Another important thing is to debug. Debugging is sort of like teaching yourself again, or

00:02:06.420 --> 00:02:13.500
removing bad coding habits. And the main things you want to do when debugging is just finding general errors in your code.

00:02:13.500 --> 00:02:16.440
We can do this by doing things like alerts.

00:02:16.460 --> 00:02:23.340
Or we can even use the built-in or $.writeln() function, and we can tell the user things

00:02:24.230 --> 00:02:30.759
while they're going through the script. And to see an alert, it'll automatically pop up on the screen. But to see a

00:02:30.980 --> 00:02:35.940
system writeln() we need to go to Window and Javascript Console.

00:02:36.120 --> 00:02:41.940
And any system level messages will be displayed inside of this console.

00:02:41.940 --> 00:02:46.240
Along with debugging you'll also want to debug with different versions of what you're coding for.

00:02:46.520 --> 00:02:53.740
So if you have a script that you've only been using Adobe After Effects 2018 for, well, it might not work in say

00:02:54.110 --> 00:02:56.139
cs6 or CC 2014.

00:02:56.600 --> 00:03:03.939
There are some features that aren't implemented in the older versions of After Effects that have been put in recently. So always be sure to

00:03:03.940 --> 00:03:09.669
be testing. Not just an ExtendScript, but also in the versions of After Effects you're expecting to work in.

00:03:10.250 --> 00:03:15.549
Also along those lines, not just on Windows, but you also want to test things on Mac.

00:03:16.340 --> 00:03:23.530
Because often some code won't work on Mac. Especially if you're using folder structures. The next piece of advice

00:03:23.530 --> 00:03:28.390
I could give you is to make sure you visit any forums for After Effects scripting.

00:03:28.459 --> 00:03:34.449
These are the most helpful places to go to, if your answers cannot be found in your head,

00:03:34.549 --> 00:03:40.599
in the UI guide in the scripting guide or just talking to close friends who know about scripting.

00:03:41.239 --> 00:03:46.059
I find that even when I can't come up with something after days of practice and trial and error,

00:03:46.220 --> 00:03:52.089
or talking to my friends, the last place and where most of the answers will be found is here.

00:03:52.670 --> 00:03:54.440
Of course before you post something

00:03:54.440 --> 00:04:00.339
Be sure to search through on the forms first. If you just post something and that thread already exists somewhere,

00:04:00.739 --> 00:04:03.339
you're not going to get the best welcome to the community.

00:04:04.130 --> 00:04:07.869
Another hyper important thing is to use object level thinking.

00:04:08.810 --> 00:04:12.519
Inside of ExtendScript we can load up the Object Model Viewer (OMV)

00:04:12.650 --> 00:04:16.959
Which for us will describe all of the JavaScript core classes built into JavaScript Extended.

00:04:17.630 --> 00:04:21.700
As well as we can have access to script UI classes,

00:04:22.490 --> 00:04:24.490
and program specific classes.

00:04:24.650 --> 00:04:26.500
This is very important because

00:04:26.500 --> 00:04:32.529
we can go in here and say look at, if I want to access a file, I can see all of the constructors,

00:04:32.780 --> 00:04:34.809
Instances, and classes involved with it.

00:04:35.020 --> 00:04:42.700
All the attributes and properties that I can call, read and write from it. As well as you can see the actions we can apply to it.

00:04:42.760 --> 00:04:50.740
Knowing how different object levels work in After Effects is incredibly important, because I often find myself messing up lines of code because I accidentally

00:04:51.140 --> 00:04:56.979
misunderstood part of the scripting guide, or how the object model works. For example if I had a

00:04:57.350 --> 00:05:01.480
composition, and I wanted to add a layer to it like a solid,

00:05:01.480 --> 00:05:04.299
I would typically just say comp.addSolid(),

00:05:04.610 --> 00:05:12.070
but anyone who's used After Effects scripting knows that that would not work because we need to have comp.layers.addSolid();

00:05:12.290 --> 00:05:19.359
The same thing goes for any app.project level things. If we wanted to say add an AV item or something,

00:05:19.669 --> 00:05:24.369
that would not work, because we need to also reference the project items.

00:05:24.740 --> 00:05:27.280
So it's important to know the object level,

00:05:27.280 --> 00:05:32.769
and how everything is organized, which you can also again see inside of the scripting guide.

00:05:33.169 --> 00:05:39.728
Has a nice object model view here, and also inside of the object model viewer inside of extend script,

00:05:39.740 --> 00:05:42.820
We can also view this for UI classes and others.

00:05:44.030 --> 00:05:48.160
Another way to learn although a lot harder is to watch tutorials.

00:05:48.160 --> 00:05:53.979
The only ones I can recommend are my own and David Torno's, where there's about 19 or so tutorials

00:05:53.980 --> 00:05:57.880
I believe on his website. videoprocoalition.com

00:05:57.980 --> 00:06:02.500
But you want to watch lots of tutorials, not just to learn but also to get ideas.

00:06:03.020 --> 00:06:08.109
Which you can also get from websites like VideoHive in the After Effects script category.

00:06:08.240 --> 00:06:15.700
But of course don't steal from these artists. Just get ideas and see if you can come up with anything more unique than them.

00:06:16.400 --> 00:06:18.920
The final piece of advice I can give to you guys

00:06:23.520 --> 00:06:29.300
The best way to learn anything is to do it by yourself and force yourself to do it.

00:06:29.300 --> 00:06:36.110
The way I initially learned how to use After Effects scripts was just to set a goal and slowly work towards it.

00:06:36.110 --> 00:06:42.080
I first told myself, okay, I want to have a script that can turn on and off all my layers.

00:06:42.630 --> 00:06:44.630
So what do I first need to do?

00:06:44.940 --> 00:06:51.200
Well the first thing I should probably do is learn how to turn off a layer and turn on a layer with the script.

00:06:51.690 --> 00:06:55.459
Then I need to figure out how I can do it to multiple layers.

00:06:55.950 --> 00:07:03.020
In this case all of them. And the biggest thing is just to push through any struggles that you have, that's the fun part,

00:07:03.320 --> 00:07:05.460
and the hard part about coding is

00:07:05.620 --> 00:07:07.060
problem-solving.

00:07:07.220 --> 00:07:11.980
Although we're not doing high level math or computer science inside of JavaScript right now,

00:07:12.660 --> 00:07:14.280
There's still gonna be a lot of

00:07:14.280 --> 00:07:16.549
problems and some code bugs that are gonna

00:07:16.550 --> 00:07:23.270
take forever to fix, and once you realize that there's just an extra comma or a period, you're gonna feel so stupid afterwards.

00:07:23.700 --> 00:07:28.759
But you'll know for next time to look out for that. And it's those little things that you learn along the way,

00:07:28.890 --> 00:07:33.679
that will just help you become a lot better of a programmer. So that's gonna be it for this tutorial guys.

00:07:33.680 --> 00:07:39.169
I hope you enjoyed. That's how you can teach yourself, or start learning After Effects Scripting by yourself.

